Akh'enet is a ruined legal-mortuary relay city between the Southern Oasis and the pyramid approach roads. It bound oasis water law to pyramid funerary authority: caravans, bodies, debt, relics, and verdicts all moved through Akh'enet on their way to deeper desert powers. Its oldest creed: "What is unrecorded becomes famine." Founded as the Third Southern Register — a Keeper-era calibrated road gate where surveyors reconciled caravan manifests against distance stones and water burn-rates — it expanded into a full mortuary-port city under Salt Ledger dynasts, adding caravan hospitals, embalmer terraces, and witness courts. Two institutions defined the Salt Ledger era: the Reed Ledger Wardens (practical water law and convoy accountability) and the Jackal Balance Court (debt adjudication fused with funerary sentence rites). Their administrative categories bled together: water quotas carried funerary annotations; death ledgers carried ration penalties. Moon Sovereign doctrine then expanded Akh'enet into a proving ground for the Doctrine of the Ninth Descent — testimony "purified" through subterranean silence chambers. The Bellwind Collapse ended the functioning city: tremors ruptured undersluice infrastructure, causing aquifer backflow with saline surge into civic cisterns, continuous resonance bell activation, and mass ledger loss as archive vaults flooded and silted. Current factions in the ruin: Reed Ledger Wardens (water-first, records second, ritual never above either), Moon Sepulchrists (range from sincere theologians to militant revivalists seeking to reopen the Nadir Palace engine), Salt Jackal Reclaimers (relic brokers and forged-seal traffickers), and Caravan Freeholds (neutral hostels preserving practical memory of who can be paid and where water still rises).

