Akh'enet's hydraulic infrastructure is the material substrate underneath its institutional history. The city was built on fractured limestone and basalt intrusions connected indirectly to the Deepwell Confluence aquifer network. The Keeper-era calibration works — road gradients, drainage cuts, shadow-line anchor points built to absurd precision — still funnel movement better than newer improvisations even in ruin. The Bellwind Collapse was a hydraulic failure before it was an institutional one: tremor chains and pressure faults in undersluice infrastructure ruptured deep regulator shafts, causing aquifer backflow with saline surge into civic cisterns. The resonance bells sounding continuously without human operation and the mass ledger flooding were consequences of hydraulic failure — engineering failure that the Jackal Balance Court interpreted as spiritual judgment. This is the central misclassification: tremor chains and pressure faults are geological processes. Saline aquifer backflow under fracture stress is a predictable consequence of undersluice infrastructure built on limestone over a pressured aquifer without adequate fault-monitoring. The Moon Sepulchrists' interpretation (divine judgment requiring restoration of sentence-state) and the Reed Ledger Wardens' interpretation (engineering failure requiring secular emergency control) are not equally valid readings of the same event. One engages with the geological and hydraulic causes; the other does not. The cistern's current broken pressure logic, irregular echoes, and bioluminescent mineral films are consequences of unmanaged infrastructure, not active judgment.

