Akh'enet's founding creed — "What is unrecorded becomes famine" — is an empirical claim whose truth can be measured against the city's own history. During the Keeper era, when recording was systematic and calibrated (thirst oaths, silt tallies, witness stones paired with route distance and cistern allocation), the road gate functioned: caravans moved, deaths were recorded and compensated, route viability was forecasted. During the Jackal Balance Court's dominance, when records began carrying both civic and metaphysical weight (water quotas with funerary annotations, death ledgers with ration penalties), the categories blurred and predictability declined. During the Bellwind Collapse, mass ledger loss destroyed the measurement baseline: with records gone, the city could not assess its own state. The founding creed's truth in reverse: the unrecorded did become famine — not immediately, but the destruction of records made it impossible to allocate resources, adjudicate claims, or coordinate response with the empirical grounding that Keeper-era documentation provided. The current state of Akh'enet — multiple factions claiming legitimacy from partial records they cannot fully interpret — is the downstream consequence of the Bellwind's mass record destruction. Each faction's claim to authority depends on incomplete documentation of the institutional chains that would validate the claim. The empirical resolution of which faction has legitimate authority requires records that no longer exist in recoverable form.
